overall tempering of anti-gay rhetoric in the 1990s, opponents of equality are formidable, and standing up for sexual minorities is still widely thought to be politically risky.Rayside documents a high-profile controversy in each of three countries: gays and lesbians in the military in the United States, sexual orientation and human rights legislation in Canada, and the age-of-consent battle in the United Kingdom. In addition, in-depth interviews of openly gay elected officials from three countries—U.S. Congressman Barney Frank, Canadian Member of Parliament Svend Robinson, and British M.P. Chris Smith—provide an inside look at the political process: the negotiation of gay and lesbian policy issues on a daily basis, the attitudes of colleagues in various political parties, and the tensions created when grassroots and mainstream activism intersect with each other. The only major book to look at gay and lesbian politics in three culturally similar but politically disparate countries, On the Fringe explores the political workings and impact of a modern social movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGay liberation movementzCanada. 0aGay liberation movementzGreat Britain. 0aGay liberation movementzUnited States. 0aGaysxPolitical activityzCanada. 0aGaysxPolitical activityzGreat Britain. 0aGaysxPolitical activityzUnited States. 4aGay & Lesbian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172963840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501729638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501729638/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archiv